(324, 19, 'description', 'I have been mixed up with automotive media since the mid-1980s, when I was one of the first staffers at Automobile Magazine. I worked there from the third issue to the tenth-anniversary issue, so I?m no stranger to startups. Since then, I have been an at-home mom with my four kids for about seventeen years. They turned out to be, in birth order: a jazz guitarist; a voracious reader who was born forty years too late to be a member of the Beat Generation; a classical violinist; and my youngest, who shows promise as an automotive enthusiast. Now I''m back at JeanKnowsCars.com and prepared to stick around until age eighty, or longer.  \n\nI studied journalism at the University of Michigan and the University of Strasbourg, France. Before that, I attended a hippie boarding school in Sedona, Arizona, and then earned the distinction of dropping out of the same college where Steve Jobs dropped out (Reed College), less than a year after he did. I have also written and edited for many automotive publications and websites and for <em>Twins </em>magazine, where I wrote a regular column for several years in between driving to music lessons and on school field trips in my minivan. \n\nYes, I drive a minivan. Actually, I think minivans are awesome for their storage and people-carrying ability, for their excellent visibility, and for the fact that cops conveniently overlook how fast a mom in a minivan might be driving because they?re hoping to stop a red sports car instead. I have taken several long cross-country adventure drives in my life: excursions of 5,000 miles or more, both<em> as </em>a teenager and <em>with</em> teenagers. Florida? California? Washington State? Washington, D.C.? If there''s a plane that goes there...I''ll get in the car and drive there anyway. I strongly believe that enjoyment of cars and driving is for everybody, including me and including you.'),
